"self", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "app", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": ["This is used to set up session for your app object.\n\n```\nparam app\n\nthe Flask app object with proper configuration.\n```\n"]}, {"name": "flask_sessions.Session._get_interface", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "self", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "app", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}], "class_variables": [], "instance_variables": [], "inner_classes": [], "documentation": ["This class is used to add Server-side Session to one or more Flask\napplications.\n\nThere are two usage modes.  One is initialize the instance with a very\nspecific Flask application:\n\n```\napp = Flask(__name__)\nSession(app)\n```\n\nThe second possibility is to create the object once and configure the\napplication later:\n\n```\nsess = Session()\n\ndef create_app():\n    app = Flask(__name__)\n    sess.init_app(app)\n    return app\n```\n\nBy default Flask-Session will use {class}`NullSessionInterface`, you\nreally should configurate your app to use a different SessionInterface.\n\n:::{note}\nYou can not use `Session` instance directly, what `Session` does\nis just change the {attr}`~flask.Flask.session_interface` attribute on\nyour Flask applications.\n:::\n"]}], "exports": [{"name": "flask_sessions.FileSystemSessionInterface", "xref": {"fqname": "flask_sessions.sessions.FileSystemSessionInterface", "project": null}}, {"name": "flask_sessions.MemcachedSessionInterface", "xref": {"fqname": "flask_sessions.sessions.MemcachedSessionInterface", "project": null}}, {"name": "flask_sessions.MongoDBSessionInterface", "xref": {"fqname": "flask_sessions.sessions.MongoDBSessionInterface", "project": null}}, {"name": "flask_sessions.NullSessionInterface", "xref": {"fqname": "flask_sessions.sessions.NullSessionInterface", "project": null}}, {"name": "flask_sessions.RedisSessionInterface", "xref": {"fqname": "flask_se